but some failed OR throttled)\n- Line 229-232: `pending` when `throttled > 0` but `delivered === 0` and `failed === 0`\n- Line 235: `failed` when all failed (failed > 0, delivered === 0, throttled === 0)\n\nSo the problematic case is when some matches deliver but others are throttled. Those throttled matches are lost.\n\nActually, the event has MULTIPLE matches (multiple subscriptions). If some deliver and some are throttled, the event is marked `partial`. The throttled matches are never retried.\n\nHmm, but looking at the description again: \"When a persona is at its concurrency limit, eventBusTick.ts permanently marks the event as failed/partial — it is dead and never retried.\"\n\nSo the fix is: when throttling happens, instead of marking as `partial` or keeping as `pending`, I should use `retry_after` to defer the event and avoid re-delivering to personas that already succeeded. The key insight is that for events where all matches are throttled, I need to add a `retry_after` column and set it to `now + backoff` while keeping status as `pending`. Then I'll modify the query to only pick up events where `retry_after IS NULL OR retry_after <= datetime('now')`, so throttled events get exponential backoff instead of retrying every 2 seconds. have exponential backoff.\n\nFor the `partial` case (some delivered, some throttled), the event is still marked `partial` - which IS dead. But the requirement doesn't specifically address this case. Let me focus on the simple case first.\n\nActually wait, re-reading: \"permanently marks the event as failed/partial — it is dead and never retried\". So the requirement is asking to fix the case where events with throttled matches end up in a terminal state.\n\nLet me look at the logic again:\n```\nif (delivered > 0 && failed === 0 && throttled === 0) → 'delivered'\nelse if (delivered > 0) → 'partial'  // this includes delivered > 0 && throttled > 0\nelse if (throttled > 0) → 'pending'  // this is only when delivered === 0\nelse → 'failed'\n```\n\nNow I'm mapping out all the possible outcome combinations to understand which ones are problematic. When all matches are throttled or when throttled matches mix with failures, the event gets marked pending and immediately retries without any backoff, which could cause hammering. But when some matches deliver alongside throttled ones, the event becomes partial and stops retrying entirely - losing those throttled matches forever. The real issue is distinguishing between genuine failures that should be terminal versus throttling that needs retry logic with exponential backoff. the throttled ones need retry\n\nFor cases 2 & 4, the fundamental issue is that event-level status tracking doesn't capture per-match delivery state. Solving that properly would require per-match tracking. But the requirement says to use a simpler approach: retry_after with backoff.\n\nI think the simplest correct implementation is:\n- For the throttle-only case (case 5, 7): set retry_after with backoff, keep status as `pending`\n- For the partial case with throttling (case 2, 4): this is trickier. We could leave it as-is for now or change it to also use retry_after.\n\nActually, looking at the requirement description again: \"When the concurrency guard fires, set retry_after = now + backoff and leave status as pending.\"\n\nThis suggests that ANY time throttling happens (including partial delivery), the event should stay pending with retry_after. The re-dispatch of already-delivered matches on retry might be acceptable if executions are idempotent or the system handles duplicates. So I'll implement it as the requirement states: add retry_after and retry_count columns, set status to pending with retry_after when throttling occurs, and modify getPendingEvents to filter by retry_after. For partial delivery cases, I'll also mark them pending with retry_after, accepting that duplicate dispatch handling is out of scope. The current code already handles the all-throttled case, but the rea